                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d121">
                <head>121. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1"
                        >Shultz</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RRW_1"
                        >Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d121fn1">Source: Reagan Library, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">George Shultz</persName> Papers, President’s Evening
                        Reading September–December 1982. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-12-20">December 20, 1982</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Algeria.]</p>
                <p>3. <hi rend="italic">Mac Baldrige’s Visit to Algeria</hi>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BMHM_1">Mac Baldrige</persName>’s recent visit to Algeria was a
                    success. Mac, leading a Trade and Investment Mission, saw most of the key
                    Algerian economic decision makers and had a 90-minute meeting with President
                        <persName corresp="#p_BC_1">Bendjedid</persName>,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d121fn2">A record of the Baldrige-Bendjedid conversation is in
                        telegram 42404 from Paris, December 8. (Department of State, Central Foreign
                        Policy File, Electronic Telegrams, D820637–0093)</note> who said that
                    Algeria desires better political and economic relations with us. The <persName
                        corresp="#p_BMHM_1">Baldrige</persName> mission revealed significant
                    commercial prospects in the fields of agribusiness, water resources,
                    telecommunications, aviation and avionics, operations and maintenance services,
                    and manpower training. In the wake of Mac’s visit, the Algerian Government
                    signaled its wish to begin negotiations soon on a civil air agreement providing
                    for direct flights from Algeria to the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> and is
                    negotiating two large contracts, each in excess of $200 million, with Lockheed
                    and Boeing. President <persName corresp="#p_BC_1">Bendjedid</persName> also
                    indicated his desire for other high level <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                    visits. (<gloss target="#t_C_1">C</gloss>)</p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to Algeria.]</p>
            </div>
